// Obtener todos los productos públicos (solo activos) GET /catalog/products?page=1&limit=20&categoryId=uuid&q=search
// Obtener un producto específico con info de stock GET /catalog/products/:id
// CRUD completo para administradores GET /admin/products?page=1&limit=20&categoryId=uuid&status=active&q=search GET /admin/products/:id GET /admin/products/sku/:sku POST /admin/products PATCH /admin/products/:id DELETE /admin/products/:id

1. Does the /users endpoint have the same JWT middleware as /auth/login? No, they have different middleware configurations: /auth/login: ❌ No JWT guards - It's a public endpoint ❌ No AppContextMiddleware - Explicitly excluded in app.module.ts ✅ Public route - Listed in ConditionalPermissionsGuard public routes // app.module.ts - AppContextMiddleware exclusions { path: 'auth/login', method: RequestMethod.POST },
// ConditionalPermissionsGuard - public routes { path: '/auth/login', method: 'POST' },
/users: ✅ Has JWT guards - @<file_name> ✅ Has AppContextMiddleware - Applied to all routes except exclusions ✅ Route-specific guards - Listed in ConditionalPermissionsGuard specific guards // users.controller.ts @<file_name>
// ConditionalPermissionsGuard - routes with specific guards '/users', 2. Are all endpoints using the same JWT secret and validation logic? No, there are TWO different JWT configurations: Admin JWT (for /users, /auth endpoints): // auth.module.ts secret: config.jwtSecret, // JWT_SECRET env var signOptions: { algorithm: 'HS256' }
// jwt-access.strategy.ts jwtFromRequest: ExtractJwt.fromAuthHeaderAsBearerToken() 3. Is there a different authentication configuration for the /users route? Yes, significantly different: Middleware Stack for /users: LoggerMiddleware (all routes) AppContextMiddleware (requires X-App-Id + authenticated user) JwtAuthGuard (validates Bearer token) PermissionsGuard (checks specific permissions) Middleware Stack for /auth/login: LoggerMiddleware (all routes) No AppContextMiddleware (excluded) No JWT guards (public endpoint) No PermissionsGuard (public route) Key Differences Summary: Aspect /auth/login /users JWT Guard ❌ No ✅ JwtAuthGuard AppContextMiddleware ❌ Excluded ✅ Required Permissions ❌ Public ✅ Required X-App-Id Header ❌ Not required ✅ Required JWT Secret N/A (no validation) JWT_SECRET The root cause is confirmed: /users requires a valid JWT Bearer token in the Authorization header, while /auth/login is completely public and doesn't validate any tokens.

